    "With this Markowitz++ method, we obtain the performance listed in the second from bottom row of table 1.",
    "It is considerably better than the performance achieved by adding just one additional constraint, as in the four previous experiments, and very much better than the basic Markowitz method.",
    "Not surprisingly it achieves good performance on all metrics, with a high Sharpe ratio, reasonable tracking of our volatility target, modest turnover and leverage, and very small maximum drawdown.",
